INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArmin Geertz corrects what he sees as basic American and European tendencies to misrepresent non-Western cultures. Carefully documenting the historical role of prophecy in Hopi Indian religion, Geertz shows how prophecies about the end of the world have been created by the Hopi Traditionalist Movement and used by non-Indian movements, cults, and interest groups. Many of the seeming peculiarities of Hopi religion and culture have been invented, he says, by tourists, novelists, journalists, and scholars, and the millennial Traditionalist Movement has subtly co-authored European and American stereotypes of Indians. Geertz's richly detailed examples and persuasive arguments will be welcomed by all those interested in Native American studies, comparative religions, anthropology, and sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHopi IndiansxReligion. 0aHopi IndiansxSocial conditions. 0aHopi philosophy. 0aProphecy. 4aAmericas. 4aIndians. 4aIndigenous religions. 4aanthropology. 4aethnic studies. 4aethnology of religion. 4aethnology. 4aindigenous peoples. 4areligion. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052030610340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520311084?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520311084423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520311084/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles